title: Rumson-Fair Haven football runs by Manasquan
text:
MORE RUMSON - Rumson-Fair Haven’s Mike Ruane set the tone of the defensive side of the ball, and Bryan Hess followed suit on the offensive side of the ball, as the Bulldogs cruised to a 49-6 win over Manasquan on homecoming night at Borden Stadium.
Rumson-FH head coach Bryan Batchler watched as his defense forced three turnovers on the Warrior’s first three offensive possessions of the game.
“We have kids that are hungry and talented,” Batchler said. “They feed off each other, I can’t say enough about sophomore Chase Pfrang and Griffin Feinberg , they both did a great job tonight”
Mike Murdock also recorded a pick six for the Bulldogs in the second half of play.
RFH showcased two very good running backs on Friday night, the strong play of Bryan Hess and Matt Vecchiarelli was too much for the Warriors defense to handle.
It helps to have dual-threat quarterback Mike O’Connor behind center, he found Elijah McAllister for a 37-yard touchdown pass to put the Bulldogs up 32-0.
Throwing the football better was something Batchler hoped to see from his team on Friday night after moving McAllister into the slot. The balance of the run game seemed to open things up on the outside for O’Connor.
For now, the focus is improving day in and day out for the Bulldogs, as they hope to finish the season at 11-1.
“We are getting there,” Batchler said, “We are maybe a little ahead of where we were last year, and we were pretty good last season.”
Manasquan’s Parker Day ran for a 13-yard touchdown run in the fourth quarter.
Key play: Mike O’Connor found Matt Vecchiarelli for an 18-yard touchdown pass to put the Bulldogs up 18-0 in the first quarter.
Offensive game ball: Bryan Hess rushed for two touchdowns, including a 75-yard run in the first quarter.
Defensive game ball : RFH’s Mike Ruane had two interceptions in the first half, including a pick six on the third play of the game.
Up next: Rumson-Fair Haven will travel to Lakewood on Oct. 24, and Manasquan will host Matawan on Oct. 31.
